## 4. Processing Pipeline

### The 9-Step Pipeline

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    S1["1. Gmail Sync<br/>Fetch new emails"] --> S2["2. Filter Engine<br/>Identify financial emails"]
    S2 --> S3["3. Parser<br/>Extract structured data"]
    S3 --> S4["4. Deduplication<br/>Avoid duplicates"]
    S4 --> S5["5. Normalization<br/>Clean merchant names"]
    S5 --> S6["6. Categorization<br/>Assign category"]
    S6 --> S7["7. Storage<br/>Save transaction"]
    S7 --> S8["8. Insights Engine<br/>Update aggregates"]
    S8 --> S9["9. Dashboard/API<br/>Serve UI"]
```

### Step-by-Step Analysis

#### Step 1: Gmail Sync
- Fetch last 50–100 emails on first connect
- Subsequent syncs: only new emails since `last_synced_at`
- Filter by known senders: `alerts@hdfcbank.com`, `noreply@paytm.com`, etc.

> [!NOTE]
> Gmail API uses `historyId` for incremental sync — far more efficient than date-based polling. The `users.messages.list` endpoint with a `q` parameter can filter by sender at the API level, reducing bandwidth.

#### Step 2: Filter Engine
Classifies each email into:
- ✅ `TRANSACTION_EMAIL` → process
- ❌ `OTP` → ignore
- ❌ `PROMOTION` → ignore
- ❌ `STATEMENT` → handle differently (future)

**Keywords for detection:** `debited`, `credited`, `spent`, `transaction`, `UPI`, `NEFT`, `IMPS`

#### Step 3: Parser (Detailed in Section 5)

#### Step 4: Deduplication
**Fingerprint formula:**
```
hash(amount + date + merchant + ref_id)
```
- If fingerprint exists → skip
- Edge case: same amount, same merchant, same day, different transactions → `ref_id` disambiguates

> [!WARNING]
> If `ref_id` is missing (some banks don't include it), dedup becomes risky. Fallback: `amount + date + merchant + account_last4 + time_window(±5min)`

#### Step 5: Merchant Normalization
```
SWIGGY, SWIGGY INDIA, SWIGGY ONLINE → "Swiggy"
AMAZON PAY, AMAZON.IN, AMZN → "Amazon"
```
**Implementation:** Alias lookup table + fuzzy matching (Levenshtein distance)

#### Step 6: Categorization
**Rule-based for prototype:**
```
Swiggy, Zomato → Food
Uber, Ola → Transport
Amazon, Flipkart → Shopping
Netflix, Spotify → Subscription
```
Unknown merchants → `"Others"` category

#### Step 7–9: Storage → Insights → Dashboard
Covered in Sections 6 below.

### Automation Rules (Non-Negotiable)

| Rule | Rationale |
|------|-----------|
| Always auto-sync | Zero manual effort promise |
| Never duplicate | Data integrity |
| Always store raw | Enable re-processing |
| Always compute confidence | Enable quality filtering |
| Never block on errors | Pipeline resilience |
| Low confidence → flag but store | Don't lose data |

---

## 5. Parsing Engine

> [!CAUTION]
> This is the **single most critical and most fragile** component. If parsing fails, the entire system produces garbage. Every design decision here has outsized impact.

### Parsing Steps

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    E["Raw Email Body"] --> C1["Step 1: Email Classification<br/>debit / credit / OTP / promo"]
    C1 -->|Transaction| PM["Step 2: Pattern Matching<br/>Regex extraction"]
    C1 -->|Non-transaction| IGN["Ignore"]
    PM --> ME["Step 3: Merchant Extraction"]
    ME --> DE["Step 4: Date Extraction"]
    DE --> CS["Step 5: Confidence Scoring"]
    CS --> OUT["Structured Transaction Object"]
```

### Worked Example

**Input email:**
```
From: alerts@hdfcbank.com
Subject: Debit Alert
Body: "Rs. 450.00 debited from A/c XX1234 on 05-May-26 at SWIGGY via UPI Ref No 123456789"
```

**Step 1 — Classification:** Keywords `debited` → `DEBIT` type

**Step 2 — Amount Extraction:**
```regex
(?:Rs\.?|INR|₹)\s?(\d{1,3}(?:,\d{3})*(?:\.\d{2})?)
```
Result: `450.00`

**Step 3 — Merchant Extraction:**
```regex
(?:at|to|from|via UPI to)\s+([A-Z][A-Za-z\s]+?)(?:\s+via|\s+on|\s*$)
```
Result: `SWIGGY`

**Step 4 — Date Extraction:**
```regex
(\d{2}-[A-Z][a-z]{2}-\d{2,4})
```
Result: `05-May-26` → `2026-05-05`

**Step 5 — Confidence Scoring:**

| Signal | Found? | Score |
|--------|--------|-------|
| Amount | ✅ | +40 |
| Merchant | ✅ | +30 |
| Date | ✅ | +20 |
| Type | ✅ | +10 |
| **Total** | | **100%** → `0.92` (with small penalty for heuristic uncertainty) |

**Output:**
```json
{
  "amount": 450.00,
  "type": "debit",
  "merchant_raw": "SWIGGY",
  "merchant_normalized": "Swiggy",
  "category": "Food",
  "date": "2026-05-05",
  "account": "XX1234",
  "ref_id": "123456789",
  "confidence": 0.92
}
```

### Bank Format Variability — The Hard Problem

| Bank | Example Format |
|------|---------------|
| HDFC | `Rs. 450.00 debited from A/c XX1234 on 05-May-26 at SWIGGY` |
| SBI | `Your a/c X1234 debited by Rs450 on 05/05/26 transfer to SWIGGY` |
| ICICI | `INR 450 spent on ICICI Card XX1234 at SWIGGY on 05-May` |
| Kotak | `₹450 debited from your Kotak A/c for SWIGGY` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Each bank has its own email template. The parser needs **bank-specific rule sets**, not one universal regex. Design the parser as a **registry of bank parsers**, each with its own patterns.

### Recommended Parser Architecture
```
ParserRegistry
  ├── HDFCParser (patterns for HDFC emails)
  ├── SBIParser (patterns for SBI emails)
  ├── ICICIParser (patterns for ICICI emails)
  ├── GenericParser (fallback with loose patterns)
  └── [Future: LLM-based parser for unknown formats]
```

